<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TOON TALK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Holy Heart Attack, Batman!: He smokes. He eats fatty foods. He doesn't 
exercise. 
</P>
<P>
And all that stressful crimefighting has taken its toll. Gotham City's 
Commissioner Gordon has a massive heart attack in an issue of Batman comics on 
sale now. The storyline is a joint effort between DC Comics, the publisher of 
Batman, and the American Heart Assn. to educate the public about heart disease. 
In addition, public service advertising about heart disease, featuring the 
character of the commissioner, will appear in other DC comic books this month. 
Will Gordon recover? The heart attack saga will continue in Batman over the 
next few years. BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA122790-0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 327642 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 27, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
