</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I Hear a Symphony: Paul McCartney has gone classical. The former Beatle will 
return to his hometown of Liverpool, England, in June for the premiere of his 
first classical composition, "Liverpool Oratorio." 
</P>
<P>
The work is the semi-autobiographical tale of the life of a Liverpool war baby 
and was written with conductor Carl Davis. McCartney won't be part of the 
performance, which will feature Dame Kiri Te Kanawa and about 200 musicians and 
singers when it's performed in Liverpool Cathedral. McCartney says writing the 
piece was challenging because he had no experience in classical music as a 
child. BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, McCartney 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA122790-0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 327643 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 27, 1990, Thursday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
