<P>
BARDOT ONLY BELIEVES IN 'VERITE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brigitte Bardot, French cinema's best-known sex symbol, said today that she 
would not care if all but one of her dozens of films disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
"Everything I appeared in during that period can disappear forever; I couldn't 
care less," Bardot, 55, told the newspaper Liberation in a rare interview. 
</P>
<P>
"If only one trace of my passage on screen remained, I wish it was in 'La 
Verite' (The Truth) . . . where I truly felt I was a real actress," said 
Bardot, now a leading animal rights campaigner. 
</P>
<P>
Filmed in 1960 by Henri-Georges Clouzot, "La Verite" portrayed a real incident 
in which a young Frenchwoman murdered her lover. It won an Oscar for best 
foreign film. 
</P>
<P>
"For me, the cinema is linked to such confusion in my (personal) life that I 
never wish to hear about it again and, obviously, never want to act again," 
said Bardot, whose last screen appearance was in 1973. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Brigitte Bardot 
</P>
